    "summary": "Hatshepsut reigned as pharaoh of Egypt from approximately 1479 to 1458 BC, initially as regent for her stepson Thutmose III and eventually as a full pharaoh in her own right. She was one of ancient history's most successful female rulers, overseeing a period of prosperity and ambitious building projects despite the traditionally male-dominated nature of the pharaonic office. She adopted male regalia and titles in official representations, appearing in statues with the royal beard and kilt.\n\nHatshepsut is celebrated for her trading expedition to the land of Punt, a mysterious and distant region — possibly modern Eritrea or Somalia — from which Egyptian ships returned laden with incense trees, myrrh, ebony, ivory, gold, and live animals. The expedition is depicted in extraordinary detail on the walls of her magnificent mortuary temple at Deir el-Bahri, which remains one of the finest architectural achievements of [[event:60|New Kingdom Egypt]]. She also erected two enormous obelisks at the [[event:1885|Karnak Temple complex]] and conducted successful military campaigns in Nubia and the Levant.\n\nAfter Hatshepsut's death, Thutmose III systematically erased her name and image from monuments, replacing her figures with those of himself or his father. The reasons for this campaign of damnatio memoriae — whether personal enmity, political calculation, or a desire to eliminate the precedent of female rule — remain debated. Her identity was rediscovered only in the nineteenth century through careful archaeological analysis, and she is now recognized as one of the most capable rulers of the New Kingdom.",
